
🔥 1. Cyber Security Vulnerabilities (5M)
Cyber Security Vulnerabilities are weaknesses or flaws in systems, networks, or applications that
can be exploited by attackers to gain unauthorized access or cause damage.
These vulnerabilities arise due to:
● Software bugs
● Misconfiguration
● Weak passwords
● Outdated systems
Examples:
● Malware
● Phishing attacks
● Ransomware
● Data breaches
Conclusion: Identifying and fixing vulnerabilities is essential to protect systems and sensitive data.



🔥 2. Access Control (5M)
Access Control is a security technique that restricts access to resources only to authorized users.
It ensures:
● Authentication (who you are)
● Authorization (what you can access)
Types:
● Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
● Mandatory Access Control (MAC)
● Discretionary Access Control (DAC)
● Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)
Importance:
● Prevents unauthorized access
● Protects sensitive data



🔥 3. Authentication & Types (5M)
Authentication is the process of verifying the identity of a user before granting access.
Steps:
● Identification
● Verification
● Validation
Types of Authentication:
● Single Factor Authentication
● Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
● Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)
● Biometric Authentication
● One-Time Password (OTP)
Conclusion: Authentication ensures only authorized users can access systems.



🔥 4. SSL Authentication (5M)
SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) is a security protocol used to encrypt communication between a client
and a server.
Working:
● Establishes secure connection
● Encrypts data transmission
● Uses digital certificates
Features:
● Data confidentiality
● Data integrity
● Authentication of server
Example: HTTPS websites use SSL for secure browsing.



🔥 5. Denial of Service (DoS) (5M)
Denial of Service (DoS) is an attack that makes a system or network unavailable to users.
Types:
● DoS (single attacker)
● DDoS (multiple attackers)
Effects:
● Server crash
● Slow performance
● Service unavailability
Conclusion: DoS attacks disrupt normal operations of systems.



🔥 6. Firewalls & IDS (5M)
Firewall:
A firewall is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing traffic.
Types:
● Packet filtering
● Stateful firewall
● Proxy firewall
IDS (Intrusion Detection System):
IDS monitors network activity to detect malicious actions.
Types:
● NIDS (Network-based)
● HIDS (Host-based)
Conclusion: Firewalls prevent attacks, while IDS detects them.



🔥 7. Cyber Security (5M)
Cyber Security is the practice of protecting systems, networks, and data from cyber attacks.
It ensures:
● Confidentiality
● Integrity
● Availability
Uses:
● Protects sensitive data
● Prevents cyber attacks
● Ensures safe communication
Conclusion: Cyber security is essential for digital protection.




🔥 8. Cyber Criminals (5M)
Cyber criminals are individuals or groups who use computers and networks to perform illegal
activities.
Types:
● Black-hat hackers
● Gray-hat hackers
● White-hat hackers
Activities:
● Hacking
● Identity theft
● Fraud
● Data theft
Conclusion: Cyber criminals exploit system vulnerabilities for personal gain.



🔥 9. Governance Challenges & Constraints (5M)
Internet governance faces several challenges:
● Complexity of stakeholders
● Jurisdiction issues
● Cybersecurity threats
● Privacy concerns
● Digital divide
● Content regulation
● Intellectual property issues
Conclusion: These challenges make internet regulation difficult.




🔥 10. Hacking with Example (5M)
Hacking is the process of gaining unauthorized access to a computer system or network.
Example:
An attacker uses SQL Injection to access a database and steal user information.
Types:
● Ethical hacking
● Malicious hacking
Conclusion: Hacking can be harmful if done without permission.




🔥 11. CIA Triad (5M)
CIA Triad is the foundation of cyber security.
Components:
● Confidentiality – Protect data from unauthorized access
● Integrity – Ensure data accuracy
● Availability – Ensure data is accessible
Conclusion: CIA triad ensures secure information systems.



🔥 12. Confidentiality with Example (5M)
Confidentiality ensures that sensitive information is accessible only to authorized users.
Methods:
● Encryption
● Password protection
● Access control
Example:
Bank account details are accessible only to the account holder.
Conclusion: Confidentiality protects privacy and sensitive data.

